“[i]n the country, the act of abortion is absolved under three conditions: (a) abortion is committed by a physician and has been medically determined that the woman is in danger of losing her life or undergoing physical or psychological injury due to pregnancy; (b) the pregnancy is the result of an attempted rape; (c) the mother’s economic or cultural means cannot sustain a child but the child’s needs can be met. These exemptions still leave abortion as a crime. Of course, there are people who consider that women are under serious economic pressure and if the family does not have money to feed the child or to sustain him or her, they will not be able to care about unwanted or non-wanted children. As a result, it leads to abortions resulting in less women being ostracised because it is difficult to believe that women whose husbands are savvy in rape will voluntary decide on this act (Ngonghala, 2008).”

The CEDAW has recommended that the protection of women’s rights be undertaken through the guarantee of an adequate standard of living, ensuring economic resources and employment opportunities, the universalisation of literacy and education programs, mass media initiatives, and cultural policies (Ngonghala, 2008).
